  "experiments_summary": "The experiments evaluated LLM-based extraction of synthesis procedures from scientific papers into PROV-DM-compliant graphs. A test set of 25 papers (37 synthesis procedures) was manually annotated by a domain expert, with 5 additional papers used as in-context examples. Three OpenAI models were compared: GPT-4.1 mini, GPT-4.1, and o4-mini. Evaluation metrics included collection rate (ability to identify all procedures in a paper), and extraction performance measured by precision, recall, and F1-score at two levels: (1) structural level (correctness of nodes and edges) and (2) parametric level (correctness of node attributes). Zero-shot and one-shot prompting strategies were tested, with one-shot experiments varying the complexity of in-context examples. String matching for evaluation used normalization (lowercasing, special character removal) and allowed multiple acceptable variants for ground truth elements. The final dataset was constructed by applying the best-performing configuration (o4-mini with one-shot prompting using the most complex example) to 1,616 papers, yielding 2,367 synthesis procedures from 1,568 papers. Graph structure analysis examined node count distributions and extracted synthesis backbones for different material classes using forward co-occurrence frequency matrices of activity nodes."
